data:
The EVS project "Everyone is learning” takes place in Narva, Estonia, within 15 months from 01.08.2015 to 01.11.2016. It brings to Narva 6 EVS volunteers from Germany, Hungary, Italy, Portugal, Slovenia and UK to make their voluntary services in local communities. Volunteers will be received by 5 organizations: VitaTiim NGO, Sädemeke, Tuluke and Potsataja kindergartens and Narva Vanalinna State School. Moreover, several partnering organizations - Narva Young Sailors' Club, Narva Kesklinna Gymnasium, Narva Kreenholmi Gymnasium, will be involved into cooperation with volunteers more actively.

The main goal of the project is to encourage intercultural dialogue and learning through providing international experience at local community and promoting learning mobility. The objectives of the project are: 
- to increase intercultural sensitivity in Ida-Virumaa community;
- to increase positive attitude and support to cultural diversity in Ida-Virumaa community through experience of working, living and learning together with EVS volunteers;
- to increase number of Ida-Virumaa young people and organisations engaged in EVS through raising positive awareness about European Voluntary Service as learning service and creating personal links to EVS volunteers;
- to broaden young people's and their parents' new perspectives on the world and career development opportunities through bringing up EVS volunteers' personal life and career stories.

Every volunteer will have specific activities and programmes with individual priorities and objectives depending on his/her interests, needs, competences and RO's needs and activities. Though the volunteers are expected to work in a strong cooperation with each other as well to increase an intercultural and learning dimension and strengthen positive influence in local community. The volunteers wil be of a great support for organizations’ daily activities, for making changes in the routine, bringing new ideas and developing new initiatives together with staff of receiving organizations. All activities are mostly based on practical experience as well as non-formal and informal learning.

As a result and potential longterm benefit we expect local young people and organizations to develop open-mindedness and flexibility, become more open for intercultural dialogue and willing to actively participate in social life and learning mobilities. We expect to increase participation in EVS both amongst young people and organizations. Moreover, it is expected that 6 EVS volunteers will essentially develop they professional and key competences and gain self-confidence, what help them to be happy, successful and productive in their careers.

"From Good to Great" envisages implementation of long-term EVS activity of volunteer from Great Britain in Russia.
The project's aim is to spread information about non-formal education methods among youth of Nizhny Novgorod region.
Involvement of foreign volunteer into such initiative could give possibilities to use peer education methods, to adopt experience of European countries and to make youth programs more attractive for youth.

The theme of the project is dissemination of international youth social programs and projects and other possibilities for international youth cooperation among Russian youth. So the objectives of the project are:
1) to increase interest to European culture, language, history, art of Russian youth;
2) to create the kind social atmosphere in SFERA, the workcamps or other places of work – friends, interesting spending of spare time, personal development;
3) to involve Russian volunteers into work with such groups of youth;
4) to adopt the world  international experience of work with youth to Russian conditions and to show staff of Russian NGOs other way of working, to teach them European style;
5) to participate, lead and co-ordinate activities aimed inclusion of disadvantaged youth into international youth programs.

The project meets aim of EVS, because it is directed on development of solidarity and promotion of active citizenship and mutual understanding among young people. First of all, the volunteer will show his culture, will find new contacts. All these activities will be connected with European culture, thus the mutual understanding among volunteer and Russian youth will be developed. Besides, the EVS volunteer will increase interest to foreign cultures and languages, will try to break some stereotypes and as a result he will help Russians to develop tolerance to other people.

Also, the priorities of the Erasmus+ Programme are met by context of the project – the volunteer in realising his own project can influence the community by this way as well as involve Russian volunteers to participation of this project. Youth in Europe are much more involved in non-fornal education than in Russia, and a volunteer will try to smooth over these differences promoting European awareness by this way. So Erasmus+ priorities are matched by the project. As it’s planned that the volunteer will actively involve Russian NGOs into international activities, and help them raising at this new challenge, it’ll contribute to developing the quality of support systems for youth activities and the capabilities of civil society organisations in the youth field. Presence of European volunteer in youth organization will give added value to the activities implemented, as it’ll help local volunteers get to know European culture, values and mentality better, and thus – break stereotypes. 

It’s also important to note, that through the project activities volunteer will help unemployed youth in Nizhny Novgorod, providing information about experience in European Union and giving them the opportunity and most importantly, information on how to take part in various youth initiatives across Europe. Needless to say, the project will stimulate sense of initiative and entrepreneurship, creativity, because of the specifics of hosting organization’s work. As Russian youth has less opportunities to go abroad and learn more about problems tackled nowadays in European societies, volunteer will be kind of “window” for local youth, providing information about environmental issues discussed nowadays in EU.
